column1: 140027;instagram;2018-11-28 17:57:53;FALSE;"#bookreview - feminism is for everybody: passionate politics (2000) by bell hooks
bell hooks spearheaded the history of feminism in the usa and its evolution ever since. the book is chock-full of compelling insights. to start
column2: she exposed and linked feminism to daily societal issues: reproductive rights
column4: unequal pay and homophobia to name a few. she clearly explained to what extent sexism is anchored in our culture
column5: heart and minds. both men and women hold equally sexist thoughts and actions in our daily life - the author included. and without consciousness
column6: we are trapped to our ideas learned within our patriarchal education over and over. our main hurdle is to be aware of our inner thoughts and challenge them: ‚Äúthe enemy within must be transformed before we can confront the enemy outside.‚Äù bell hooks also put into perspective that feminism messages were first conveyed through a patriarchal mass media. when it was covered
column7: it was indeed through patriarchal men‚Äôs eyes
column8: namely depicting misguided of so-called ‚Äòextremist feminism‚Äô. growing up in a traditional chinese family
column9: i used to binge watch american tv series (tv was my babysitter and friends were - and still are - my all time favorite since age 6). and even today
column10: i stumbleupon episodes and still laugh at their jokes that i heard hundred times. as i‚Äôm increasingly conscious
column11: i‚Äôve realised how the show put forward sexist script
column13: gender identites etc. i never questioned myself during my upbringing - let alone the lack of diversity representation. feminist consciousness-raising does make me confused between what is right with what i like(d): it makes me perceive our society and life in general
column15: and not take anything from granted. it‚Äôs not an easy mental exercise
column16: but it's worth it. what has feminism done to you? -- read the book to grasp a good understanding of institutionalized sexism and apply her call to action!

column1: 140115;instagram;2018-11-28 19:54:00;FALSE;"i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.
steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?
abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me
column2: a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

column1: the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the fake content - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking a real responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

column1: a new way to report sexual misconduct in the entertainment industry is here! .
it‚Äôs been more than a year since #metoo turned into a global movement and yet
column2: little has changed. as time ticks on
column3: we‚Äôre still left wondering - are we any less vulnerable from the abuses of power?  what do we actually do if we have been harassed or assaulted?  where can we report? @voices_in_action is a survivor-led organization that offers safe and confidential place to report incidents of sexual misconduct. we will also provide an alert if an assailant has been reported by more than one victim with the ability to connect through our team of attorneys under confidentiality and privilege. voices in action empowers survivors with the knowledge that they are not alone and their voice matters. it‚Äôs time to turn awareness into action. i am #provoice. #voicesinaction to help support a safer
column4: more equitable and inclusive industry - please click link in bio. every little bit helps get us one step closer!  in deep gratitude

column2: friends and candle light üíô thank you for everyone who has been wishing me a happy birthday and sending me beautiful messages of love!

column1: also. i thought i would share a commitment i am making to myself today
like many people i have spent my life dealing with low self esteem and insecurity pertaining to what i think i should be
column2: should have accomplished or need to be in order to be worthy of love.

column1: not having ever felt worthy made working towards goals much more difficult than it should be. and being concerned with how others saw me has stopped me in more areas of my life than i care to admit
column2: kept me in abusive situations for years and seemingly stolen so much time i could have otherwise spent being happy & more effectively protecting ecosystems
column3: standing up for the vulnerable and just all around serving the world.

column1: my commitment (recognizing that it will be a journey) is to live more freely
column3: not be afraid of letting people see me do bad (or being afraid and doing it anyway) and trying even harder to remind myself that a failure doesn't equal never being worthy of love or being disposable.

column1: when something means a lot to you it can be a struggle to practice non-attachment to doing well and when you struggle with feeling good enough
column2: doing bad can feel like further realization that you will not be loved which can be an ultimately crippling feeling & stop all progress.

column1: sometimes taking yourself out of the game occurs as less painful. (ps. the sharp pains of self discovery is better than the life long pains of suppressing yourself)
something i have learned is that your brain doesn't know what is or isn't real when you imagine it vividly. and what you think about on a consistent basis is what you experience. (thanks tr)

column3: we‚Äôre still left wondering - are we any less vulnerable from the abuses of power?  what do we actually do if we have been harassed or assaulted? where can we report? @voices_in_action is a survivor-led organization that offers safe and confidential place to report incidents of sexual misconduct. we will also provide an alert if an assailant has been reported by more than one victim with the ability to connect through our team of attorneys under confidentiality and privilege. voices in action empowers survivors with the knowledge that they are not alone and their voice matters. it‚Äôs time to turn awareness into action. i am #provoice.

column1: 140510;instagram;2018-11-29 07:14:56;FALSE;"hi everyone... as some of you may know
column2: i recently joined norwalk la mirada unified's sub pool in an effort to give back to the community that raised me. additionally
column3: for this past month i've been working on a book  called #thesingingsub for @nanowrimo and i'm expecting to complete it by 11/30. as painful as this was to write out
column4: i know in my heart of hearts that it was the right thing to do in order to not only educate and inspire my students
column5: but most importantly to protect them. i wrote this per the request of norwalk high's asb in order to address their concern over a particular faculty member whom they felt did not have their best interest at heart. all students
column7: deserve to feel safe and comfortable at their schools. today
column8: i relinquish my 13 years of silence in exchange for a voice that speaks for the voiceless
column9: and i pray that my story encourages more women and girls to develop the courage to also come forward with their own. may we raise one another up to face our abusers with courage and hold them accountable so they may never be allowed to break another young girl's spirit ever again.

column1: 140676;instagram;2018-11-29 13:06:08;TRUE;;"as part of the un women's #16daysofactivism against gender-based violence campaign
column2: ruman project is exploring how religious communities and faith can play a role in ending violence against women.
we're looking at religions for peace
column3: an international organisation of faith groups. in their report
column4: 'restoring dignity: a toolkit for religious communities to end violence against women'
column5: the organisation explores the concrete actions faith communities can take together in this work.

column1: in an extract from the report
column3: ""religious leaders and communities of faith have the moral authority and the responsibility to work together
column4: in a spirit of multi-faith collaboration
column5: to promote and protect the inviolable dignity of women and girls. people of faith have a unique and unparalleled potential
column7: to be powerful agents of prevention
column8: education and advocacy to end violence against women.""

column1: more than any other civil society representatives
column2: people of faith have the experience of serving individuals and communities in body
column4: and their expertise is greatly needed in the inter-religious task of creating a safe and healthy world for all women and girls.""

column1: we've been discussing introspective questions that can help you on your journey to healing. yesterday was all about asking for what you need from the people in your life. so today
column2: we have to ask what happens if you ask for what you need and they say no
column3: because this is a real possibility. the truth is
column4: you will have to figure out how to continue on your journey without these particular needs being met by said individual(s). where possible
column5: you may have to look for your needs to be met by others who are willing to give you what you need. keep in mind however
column6: this has to be done in a healthy way and not in a manner that causes you to form bonds and relationships that are built on co-dependence or unrealistic expectations and demands. you may also have to assess whether what you're asking for is truly needed and if you can move forward in a positive and healthy way without it. these are areas that a good counselor can help you work through for your continued healing. remember
